caption: Went the first day open since covid pandemic. I REALLY wanted to like it but the food was just barely ok. Baked mac/cheese tasted like it was from the box (powder cheese mix). Service was above average, attentive but not oppressive.  I had carpaccio and Mac and cheese with a non- alcoholic beverage.  Over  $37 with tax and tip.  This is on Capitol Hill, in sight of the US Capitol so we know it won't be cheap. Neither did was exceptional, the counterpoint in the carpaccio was small pieces of very hot pepper. Every time I have eaten here it was delightful. Tonight's dinner was outstanding. The Amish fried boneless chicken thighs in foie gras butter/creme fraiche potatoes was so satisfying and delicious. The oxtail and short rib rigatoni was also sensational. There is a kids menu even though it was not posted on the web. Service was attentive and thoughtful.

It was very nice and the food was good. My only issue was I ordered hot water for tea and my mug had a long piece of hair in it. That was a big turn off for me.

Art & Soul is a charming Southern cuisine restaurant with decent menu selections. The portions, however, are on the measly side. I was still hungry after my meal, and the dessert menu did not offer a remedy.  I ordered the shrimp and grits, which consisted of approximately one serving-spoon of grits and four shrimp.  It is important to realize; the portions are small, but the food tastes great. The prices are a bit steep for what you get. We do not have an issue paying for expensive meals, but I'm just giving folks a heads-up for anyone anticipating a typical Southern cuisine portioned meal.  Also, heed the warning regarding off-list drinks.  Do not order cocktails that are not on the cocktail list, even if the server assures you of the bartender's ability to do so. I ordered a Moscow Mule, and it tasted more like a Moscow Hyena – just awful! The atmosphere indoors is relaxed and cozy, and the outdoor seating is refreshing. There is metered street parking (if you are lucky), and there is also parking available in the Liaison Hotel’s parking lot. Overall, this is a lovely spot with a distinctive twist on Southern cuisine.

There's options for the vegetarians of the group and there's a nice selection of wines as well as a dessert menu (I highly recommend the peach cobbler!) A great place to visit and I will more than likely visit again.

I have never been disappointed when visiting Art and Soul.  They do a lot of Southern-style cooking very well.  My one knock is that they try to fuse and fancy it up in ways that just doesn't mesh well with down-home cooking.  That being said, sometime it works very well, such as the slow-smoked pulled pork sandwich, which has Korean elements with a kimchi slaw on it.  I have been a few times, but the last time was Summer Restaurant Week and I will be back again.  It's not perfect, but consistently quality.  I would also recommend it to you for events,  I have been to several receptions here and they do a great job.

The food is absolutely delicious and the service impeccable. There are two dishes in particular, both appetizers, that are making my mouth water just thinking about them, and I feel like I would be remiss if I didn’t recommend them to everyone. The Tartare is unique; I’ve never had tartare spiced with Indian flavorings before, and it is a work of art. Pairing it with Naan is a touch of genius. The scallop crudo (which I think is sadly not on the menu at the moment but will hopefully be coming back soon) is similarly exceptional. The wafer thin slices of scallop practically melt in your mouth, and their delicate flavor, combined with the cucumber, is something that I find hard to describe in words without sounding hyperbolic. Chef Alexander creates dishes that are not only exceptionally tasty but also fantastically creative.

This place is easy to overlook, as I almost did during my visit. It's inside a hotel, so you may need to employ a sharp eye.  We came during brunch, and found everything to be satisfactory. The (geechie boy) grits were fabulous, as were the chicken and waffles. The service was a little slow and our server was a little inattentive, but overall I enjoyed our visit.  Our server didn't know what "geechie boy" referred to, so I'll enlighten you - the geechee/geechie gullah are a community of people who live in South Carolina. They are the descendants of enslaved Africans, who speak their own dialect and have their own unique culture. The stories of Brer Fox and Brer Rabbit, for instance, come from the gullah culture. "Geechie Boy" is a company whose name references that culture/language.

I will preface by saying that a lot of places don't open or are super crowded on a holiday, so we were very grateful that Art and Soul had plenty of tables on the Fourth of July. No reservations needed. We came into the city for brunch and my boyfriend wanted to try Art and Soul because the chef, Art Smith, won a James Beard Award (although not for Art and Soul...for a book) and is considered an expert on Southern cuisine.  That day, I was very much in the mood for pancakes so I ordered the lemon pancakes ($12). My boyfriend ordered the BLT Benedict ($15) with a side of mac and cheese, and our friend ordered the three egg omelet ($14). The pancakes were huge! Three stacked pancakes, maple syrup, and a side of seasonal fruits. Fresh fruits included watermelon, honeydew, pineapple, blackberries, raspberries, and strawberries. I fulfilled my craving and got my dosage of five fruits a day. The pancakes were good but I think it's pretty hard for a restaurant of this caliber to mess up pancakes.  My boyfriend enjoyed his BLT Benedict, which came as two poached eggs on some bacon, alongside some watercress and potatoes. It looked really good and unlike some other places that serve up eggs Benedict, the side of watercress was a refreshing and balanced one.  Service was so-so. One of the other servers seemed really energetic and nice, while our server was mostly quiet but efficient. I was a little worried after reading some of the reviews where people got sick, but luckily none of us fell ill afterwards. That would have really ruined the holiday for sure! I'd come back if I'm in the area and need something quick and simple, but I wouldn't actively seek out a meal here.

We went here for breakfast our first morning in DC, and it was so good we went on our last morning too!  The service was spot-on and we found a seat as soon as we walked in. The coffee and OJ were wonderful, the coffee served with real cream!  I had the country breakfast, and both the bacon (first time) and the sage sausage (second time) were great. My companion had the french toast, and raved about it.  I really enjoyed this place, and anytime I am at the Liaison, I will definitely stop by!
A menu for dog need I say more
Amazing food.  Really amazing.  Their restaurant is top notch and is super cool!  But more important, the food is delicious and is one of those few places where Id drive in from VA to grab a bite :)

Brunch was good. The chicken and waffles were ok...chicken was delicious. They have a spicy syrup they use which was different. I Iike spicy but it would've been nice to have the option of regular syrup or the spicy one.

We stopped in to Art & Soul during restaurant week and absolutely loved it. The food and service were top notch and their super dog friendly! We sat outside (with our dog) and really enjoyed the sights and sounds of being on a busy Washington, DC street while we enjoyed our lunch.  In addition to their normal menu items they offer a really cool menu just for dogs. We ordered our dog the beef tips and rice dish and it was much larger than we expected (especially for the low price). Our food was outstanding as well but being able to bring our dog along (and have her treated like a valued member of our family) really elevated our experience to a super high level.

Had a lovely lunch here! Their burger is delicious -- moist, flavorful, and filling. Service was perfect -- always there with a refill, but never seemed to be hovering. Good mix of items to choose from. They've got a pooch patio menu, too. I'll have to come back with my dog.
Great Patio & rooftop bar

Food was good but waiter was not honest.  We had a party of 6 so unbeknownst to me they added an 18% gratuity.  Waiter brings bill and says nothing.  Brings credit card receipt and leaves the tip portion open.  Only because the bill was bit higher than I expected I reviewed noting the 18%.  Clear dishonesty by the waiter trying to get additional tip.  Been there with a number of smaller parties and will NEVER return.
Service was poor and the food was marginal

I snagged a reservation for Easter Brunch and the buffet was done very well, a wonderful array, that tasted very fresh! All of the food was absolutely delicious - my only regret is that my stomach wasn't big enough to try even more! Try the Chicken and Waffles; the crispy outer skin of the chicken, and the juicy meat inside is finger-lickin' good!
Will never go here again when I visit DC because they turned away friends of mine who wanted to dine with their pitbulls. Shame on you for discriminating, Art and Soul.

I dined at Art and Soul for Thanksgiving and the buffet selection left nothing amiss. It might become a yearly tradition. Why cook and clean when you can have an amazing home cooked meal out? My only complaint was that the bar was closed and there were a million poorly behaved children running around. Not a great combination.
Great food and great service! The fried chicken is amazing, substitute the brussels sprouts for the greens!
Poor service. Food fair. We were disappointed.  Sept 17

I had A pork dish, bacon cornbread, and rum cake for dessert. The plate looked beautiful and the meats were all delicious. The red beans and rice went great with it and the mustard jus added a little something extra. The bacon cornbread …

Today is November 22, 2012. I am pretty disappointed. I called Art and Soul for a last minute reservation for ONE for Thanksgiving Dinner, and they was not willing to accommodate one person for the holiday. I don't think that showed Southern Hospitality as specially doing a holiday like Thanksgiving. I will not be eating at Art and Soul tonight or never. I will not recommend the restaurant to anyone and will share my Thanksgiving story when ever Art and Soul is mentioned. Charlie Palmers it is!

Hubby took me here for my birthday last year. I really enjoyed the gourmet comfort food...and the service was good. My scallops were seared to perfection, and even though the place was hopping, we never felt rushed to finish our meal and leave. Left feeling satisfied.
Loved the atmosphere but the food is a little pricey. I had crab cakes and they were tasty. However, I've had better for less.

A great night with the new menu. The appetizers and mains I tried were all good, and large enough to make sides unnecessary (which saves some money). The mac'n'cheese is so good though that you have to at least share one order with the table. The pavlova, which I'm not usually a huge fan of, was a stunningly good desert.  My only complaint us the price of cocktails and wine. Way to few moderate priced options in that area. Dinner for two with cocktails and a bottle of water/wine was $250 after tip.
Extremely rude bar and wait staff. Over priced poorly reheated frozen appetizers.
Awesome crabcakes benedict. Wonderful decor and atmosphere at brunch.

excellent attention to detail, the servers can tell you anything you want to know about the eminent oprah chef's cuisine.  the hoecakes are fantastic, even if they were not what i was thinking of, more like a flatbread than anything else.  the mains were ample and tasty, and both the beer and mixed drinks were exceptional.  the beer list in particular was better than most in the area.
